node.text: Sopes are rounds of griddled masa with a little rim around the edge to hold delicious fillings. “In my house, sopes were always filled with refried black beans, pulled chicken, chopped romaine lettuce, crema, crumbled fresh cheese, and then one or two salsas and guacamole or avocado to top,” writes Epi contributor @Fanygerson. But sopes are made to be customized, she says. Learn the cooking method in the video above, and check out the link in our bio to get the recipe.

node.text: Gorditas are one of the most popular street foods in Mexico. According to @fanygerson, the translation means “little fatties,” and they’re thick masa pockets that are toasted on a comal, then stuffed with fillings. Watch the video to learn all of Gerson’s tips and tricks, then click the link in our bio for the recipe—and a sweet variation, too.

node.text: You can find tlacoyos all across Mexico—and they’re one of @fanygerson’s favorite street food snacks. The thick oval-shaped masa patties are crispy on the outside, stuffed with beans or other fillings, and piled high with a refreshing cactus salad. Here, Fany shows you how to make them, step by step, to devour right away or stock your freezer. Read more and get the recipe at the link in our bio.

node.text: “For many families, making tamales is a ritual, and younger and older generations each have specific roles in the process,” writes Epi contributor, chef @fanygerson. Here, Gerson walks you through the whole method, step by step, so you can make the fluffiest, most flavorful tamales of your life. Read more and get the recipe at the link in our bio.

node.text: When chef and cookbook author Fany Gerson (@fanygerson) first moved to New York from Mexico over 20 years ago, it wasn’t a matter of *wanting* to find good tortillas—she *needed* them. Mass-produced tortillas from supermarkets and delis had nothing in common with the supple, fragrant fresh tortillas she knew and loved in Mexico. So she started making her own—now she’s here to share her tips, step by step. Read more and get the recipe at the link in our bio. Director: @c.emanuelsmith DP: @bendewster Editor: @elliottjchrist

node.text: One day, you will be in a market, and you will pass the coconuts. They will grab your attention. You'll say to yourself, "I'm going to buy this coconut." You settle at the register, and bring your groceries home. You put most of them away. As you hold up that last item, you will ask yourself: "Why did I buy this coconut?" At least we can help answer how to open it!

node.title: 50 People Try to Crack Open a Coconut

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 17, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text:
When BA and Epi staffer Tiffany Hopkins (@itstiffyhop) set out to make bibingka cassava—the popular custardy, coconutty Filipino cake—she knew she'd have to call her mom. "My first question was, of course, about the flour. What kind did my mom use? 'What are you talking about?’ my mom replied. 'There *is* no flour.'" 

This was also true for cookbook author and chef Marvin Gapultos (@burntlumpia), whose grandmother told him the same thing. “Cassava lends a grainy texture similar to cornmeal,” says Gapultos, so “the cake itself is chewy and dense, in a good way.'” To get his recipe for this sweet, texturally complex, *flourless* cake, hit the link in bio. Photo @j_deleo, Food Styling @curlygirlcooks

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 17, 2021. May be an image of food and indoor.

node.text: Preparing salmon can be simple (just a hit of olive oil and lemon) or complex (think glazed, slow-roasted, or butter-basted). Tonight, we're having our salmon in rice bowls swimming in a coconut-ginger broth and topped with crispy, spiced panko—an elegant dinner that also happens to be quick and easy. Find this and 52 more ways to have salmon for supper at the link in bio. Photo @j_deleo, Food Styling @acstockwell

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 16, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: We're in shoulder season: that not-quite-autumn, not-quite-summer time of year when a bowl of soup is just as satisfying as a slice of ice cream cake. So let this collection of our 19 newest recipes be your guide for the next few weeks. You'll make this meaty but meatless mushroom adobo; a Sonoran-style cheese, potato, and tomato soup; frozen desserts and drinks; and hearty salads with the last, best produce summer has to offer. Grab the recipes at the link in bio. Photo @j_deleo, Food Styling @curlygirlcooks

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 16, 2021. May be an image of food and indoor.

node.text: What if, instead of croutons on your next salad, you swapped in some juicy pork meatballs? Then you grabbed, say, the rest of your late-summer cucumbers, salted and drained, to make the base for said salad. And then (stick with us here) you added buttery Castelvetrano olives, golden raisins, and toasted pine nuts, and tied the whole thing together with a swoosh of yogurt. What if you did that and it was the tastiest and easiest meal you made all week? That would be great, right? Find out why you should flip the script on your next salad at the link in bio. Recipe, Photo, and Food Styling @kendrakendrakendra

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 15, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: "As we begin to return, in fits and starts, to our pre-pandemic lives, I look forward to entertaining again," says cultural preservationist Gabrielle E.W. Carter (@gabrielle_eitienne). To celebrate, she's pulled together her dream dinner full of recipes from culinary figures of the Black diaspora. Start with this lentil and scallion salad from Southern cuisine legend Edna Lewis that's bolstered by a smoky pork stock and finished with a simple-but-pungent mustardy dressing. Make Gullah chef Sally Ann Robinson’s watermelon rind preserves. Finish off the dream dinner with honey custard from Norma Jean and Carole Darden, who run Harlem’s Miss Mamie’s Spoonbread Too (@missmamiesspoonbreadtoo). Get the complete menu at the link in bio. Photos @j_deleo, Food Styling @curlygirlcooks

node.text: Close your eyes and imagine sliding a piece of silky, chocolatey pie onto your plate—and then open your eyes and gaze upon this giant collection of the best chocolate pies that Epi has to offer. We’ve got a simple-but-sophisticated hazelnut black-bottom pie from BA and Epi Senior Director of Culinary Production Rhoda Boone Lane (@rhodaboonefood), a mile-high chocolate pie, and basically any chocolate pie you can think of—including a few you haven't! They're all waiting for you at the link in bio. Photo @j_deleo, Food Styling @acstockwell

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 14, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: Crispy chickpeas may get all the attention, but don't sleep on white beans—they want to get crispy, too. Roasting them gives them "a kind of popcorn vibe that I find especially satisfying," says former Epi editor Anna Stockwell (@acstockwell). Once you've made your crispy beans, the possibilities are endless—scatter them over salads, eat them over a swirl of yogurt, or just snack on them by the handful for a satisfying treat. Learn more about why crispy beans should be in your life at the link in bio. Photo @j_deleo, Food Styling @acstockwell

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 14, 2021. May be an image of bottle.

node.text: You know you should drink more water—but a good water bottle can be hard to find. Should you go stainless steel? Glass? Which one keeps water the coldest, the longest? We dove into the dizzying array of options and fished out the best bottles for every use. Find the one that's right for you at the link in bio. Photo: @chelsealouisekyle

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on September 13, 2021. May be an image of drink.

node.text: When life gives you pineapple rinds, make tepache! Just like the rich cuisine of Mexico, this homestyle, low-ABV drink appears in different regional variations—but a common recipe includes pineapple rinds for a subtly sweet finished product that's just as at home in a cocktail as it is served simply over ice. Learn more about tepache—including how to make it—from Epi contributor Paola Briseño-González (@paolasuavicrema) at the link in bio. node.text: Summer isn't quite over, fall hasn't officially begun: Welcome to pre-fall, arguably one of the most glorious seasons for cooking. The markets are still offering up summery ingredients, but the temperatures are now cool enough to contemplate turning on the oven. From slow-cooked green beans to baked tomatoes with toast, grab the 13 recipes we're making right now at the link in bio. Photo @j_deleo, Prop Styling @hedgehedge, Food Styling @simoncooks

Just in time to help you beat pandemic cooking fatigue, this new crop of cookbooks brings you 30-minute meals, celebrity chef-driven tomes, and plenty of vegetarian and vegan offerings. node.text: Two things make this chocolate cake shine. First, chocolate pyramids (ethically sourced and designed by @ldvega in collaboration with industrial designer Remy Labesque) melt into gooey puddles of chocolate that'll make you say, "Chocolate chips, who?" Second, the last of your late summer zucchini crept into this bake to give it a moist, pillowy texture that beautifully complements the rich chocolate and crunchy walnuts. Learn more about why you need chocolate pyramids in your life and grab the recipe for chocolate zucchini cake at the link in bio. Recipe, Photo and Food Styling @pithzester
